Editor's Note

As West Virginia hires the Drake coach, OSUâ€™s search reportedly is â€˜a messâ€™

Where Mike Boynton's salary ranked in the Big 12, what it means for Oklahoma State's future

When OU transitioned from basketball coach Lon Kruger to Porter Moser in 2021, it was a seven-day process. The University of Tulsaâ€™s 2022 transition from Frank Haith to Eric Konkol lasted nine days. At Oral Roberts University last year, Russell Springmann was promoted to the basketball head-coaching position one day after Paul Mills departed for Wichita State.

Six days after Brad Underwood bolted for Illinois in 2017, it was revealed that Mike Boynton had scored Oklahoma Stateâ€™s top job.

As of Tuesday night, 12 days had passed since OSU athletic director Chad Weiberg announced that Boynton â€” after seven seasons â€” would not be retained as the Cowboy basketball coach.

Coaches like Utah Stateâ€™s Danny Sprinkle and Drakeâ€™s Darian DeVries were believed to have been OSU targets, but they now have been hired by other schools: Sprinkle by Washington and DeVries by West Virginia.

It would be nice for a fresh and fascinating name to be added to the OSU discourse, and former Cowboy star Randy Rutherford has stepped up with a strong endorsement of a popular, Eddie Sutton-era Cowboy point guard â€“ John Lucas III.

Wednesday is the 20th anniversary of a Lucas 3-point bucket that beat St. Josephâ€™s and vaulted those 31-win Cowboys to the Final Four. Now 41, Lucas has four seasons of NBA coaching experience. He currently is a Phoenix Suns assistant.

â€œJohnâ€™s foundation is basketball. His whole life is basketball,â€ said Rutherford, who was a dynamic guard for Suttonâ€™s 1995 Final Four Cowboys and now is the McLain head coach in Tulsa.

â€œJohn is on the NBA side of it now, so I donâ€™t know if he would want the Oklahoma State job,â€ Rutherford continued. â€œBut I know he has every level of fundamental substance that you need to be a great (head coach), a great leader and a great recruiter.

â€œJohn has all of that. I know that personally.â€

Oklahoma State has a history of having hired former Cowboy athletes for OSUâ€™s top coaching jobs: Mike Gundy in football. John Smith in wrestling. Josh Holliday in baseball. Eddie Sutton in basketball.

After having transferred to OSU from Baylor, Lucas was a two-time All-Big 12 selection. In 2004, both he and Cowboy teammate Tony Allen were on the first team.

Any Oklahoma State basketball chronicle would include a few pages on Rutherfordâ€™s most famous game â€” his 45-point statement at Kansasâ€™ Allen Fieldhouse in 1995. He was close to the Sutton family, who influenced his decision to become a coach; and Rutherford today remains connected to the OSU basketball program.

In an Oklahoma State basketball update published in the Monday Tulsa World, there was a reference to CBS college basketball writer Matt Norlander having quoted a source who described Weibergâ€™s Cowboy search as â€œa mess.â€

Rutherford doesnâ€™t appreciate such criticism from anyone who doesnâ€™t actually know the details of Weibergâ€™s process.

â€œYou cannot say that this search has been a failure,â€ Rutherford said on Tuesday. â€œYou canâ€™t rush to hire someone just because there is pressure from the outside world. You canâ€™t mess around and hire a guy who isnâ€™t a good fit. We need someone to bring the program back to prominence. Itâ€™s not going to happen overnight.

â€œYou canâ€™t listen to the (chatter) from outside people. They donâ€™t know whatâ€™s happening and they donâ€™t know how a situation like this works and how complex it all is.â€

With his John Lucas III nomination, Rutherford himself has added a layer to the chatter. I confessed to Rutherford that I was aware of Lucasâ€™ career as an NBA assistant but embarrassed that I hadnâ€™t thought in previous reporting to include him as a viable OSU figure.

I had mentioned Lucas IIIâ€™s younger brother â€“ Duke associate head coach Jai Lucas â€“ but misfired on Lucas III. Rutherford didnâ€™t misfire. He had a message to convey, and he did it effectively.

Over a 12-year period, Lucas III played professional basketball in the NBA (with the Houston Rockets, Chicago Bulls, Utah Jazz, Detroit Pistons and Minnesota Timberwolves), along with several other squads in the NBA G League and in Europe and Asia.

As an NBA assistant, Lucas worked for two seasons with Timberwolves and for one with the Los Angeles Lakers. This season, he is a first-year member of the Phoenix staff.

â€œWhen youâ€™re talking about what weâ€™re trying to accomplish at Oklahoma State, yes, I definitely would talk with John and check his interest in the job,â€ Rutherford said. â€œHe checks every box (with regard) to what we would want at Oklahoma State.

â€œThere are a lot of good coaches out there, but I would support John for the OSU job. With him as the head guy, I would feel really good about the program.â€
